did.unittitle: Carnegie Endowment for International Peace pamphlet and microfilm collection
did.abstract: The Carnegie Endowment for International Peace was founded in 1910 by Andrew Carnegie. The Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, which since 1983 has again been headquartered in Washington, D.C., continues the work begun by its founders. Elihu Root and Nicholas Murray Butler were activists in a segment of a larger peace movement both in the U.S. and abroad that had its roots in the later years of the nineteenth century. This collection consists of over 7,200 items of bound pamphlets, unbound pamphlets, and microfilm. They range in date from 1817 to 1950. The topics cover world wars, international treaties and other important world events.

bioghist.head: Historical or Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The Carnegie Endowment for International Peace was founded in 1910 by Andrew Carnegie (1835-1919), who transferred to 28 selected trustees the sum of $10 million in bonds, the revenue of which was to be used to "hasten the abolition of international war." Two of the trustees, Elihu Root and Nicholas Murray Butler were very important figures in the formation of the Endowment. Elihu Root (1845-1937) served his country as Secretary of War, Secretary of State, and United States Senator. He is best remembered for his efforts to ensure international peace. He received the Nobel Peace prize in 1912 and was President of the Board of Trustees of the Carnegie Endowment from 1910 to 1925. Nicholas Murray Butler (1862-1947) served as President of Columbia University from 1902 to 1945 and shared the Nobel Peace Prize with Jane Addams in 1931. He succeeded Root as President of the Endowment, a post he held until 1945. The efforts of these men established the direction of the Endowment which for eighty-five years has encouraged peace through educational enterprises that promote international understanding and the codification of international law.

The Carnegie Endowment was headquartered in Washington, D.C., until it moved to New York City in 1950. Prior to its move, the Endowment sought an institution to purchase its library to ensure that its materials would continue to be available to researchers. The library collection was sold to The George Washington University in the year of the Endowment's move. This constituted a major acquisition for the University considering that in the fiscal year 1949/50 the University provided a total of $15,000 for the purchase of library books. The 60,000 volume collection of books, pamphlets, and documents was at that time one of the finest assembled for the study of international relations and world peace, according to an official from the Library of Congress who appraised the collection.

The Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, which since 1983 has again been headquartered in Washington, D.C., continues the work begun by its founders. Elihu Root and Nicholas Murray Butler were activists in a segment of a larger peace movement both in the U.S. and abroad that had its roots in the later years of the nineteenth century. The men and women who founded societies devoted to world peace were generally the elite of society: educators, business leaders, clergymen, journalists, etc. Periods of domestic and political turmoil and uncertainty, both at home and abroad, spurred these people to work for the cause of peace, since the promise of lasting peace meant economic and social stability. Peace societies served as forums for a national elite who held themselves responsible for molding public opinion on a wide range of issues, among them the promotion of a foreign policy that would establish a peaceful means of arbitrating international disputes. This collection of pamphlets reflect these aims and is thus a very useful research source for scholars.

scopecontent.head: Collection Scope and Content
scopecontent.p: This collection consists of over 7,200 items of bound pamphlets, unbound pamphlets, and microfilm. They range in date from 1817 to 1950. The collection covers more than following topics: the World Peace Foundation, World War I, World War II, the League of Nations, the League of Nations Union, the Treaty of Versailles, miscellaneous war, the New York Federation of Churches, International relations, national, regional, political science, social systems, economics, finance, foreign trade, labor, miscellaneous, and foreign language.
Gelman Library purchased this collection in 1950.
Please note there is no series one in this collection.

arrangement.head: Collection Organization
arrangement.p: Organized into four series (numbered 2-5): Library records, Unbound pamphlets, Microfilm, Bound manuscripts, and James B. Scott materials. Please note, there is no series one in this collection.

processinfo.head: Processing Information
processinfo.p: It may be necessary to use the previous folder number to locate a folder in a specific box.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents note
scopecontent.p: Please note there is no series one in this collection. This series contains approximately 4,350 unbound pamphlets, which include approximately 700 in foreign languages. They range in date from 1817 to 1950. Most of these fall under the "General Peace" category (about 19% of the total collection), "World War II" (13%), "National/Regional" (13%), and "International Relations/Foreign Policy" (4%). The remainder of the collection contains materials on political science, social science, economics, foreign trade, labor, and other subjects.

did.unittitle: United States and Mexican Claims Commission, United States and Mexico Claims Commission

odd.head: General note
odd.p: For background see: Claims on the part of citizens of the United States and Mexico under the Convention of July 4, 1868, between the United States and Mexico. Washington : G.P.O., 1877. Bound in green cloth over boards; spines stamped in gold Bookplates of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library. Joint commission to adjust private claims of American citizens against the Mexican government, and of Mexican citizens against the U.S. government. Met July 31, 1869-1876 Jan. 31, with the umpire finishing 1876 Nov. 20. Each country had one commissioner at a time, and they chose an umpire. Typescript (carbon copy) transcript of awards. Of 1017 claims of U.S. citizens, 186 awards; of 998 claims of Mexicans, 167 awards. William Henry Wadsworth was the American member; Mexican members included Francisco Gomez Palacio and Manuel Maria de Zamacona. Umpires were Francis Lieber, and from 1872 Sir Edward Thornton. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 17f v.1 f

Bound in green cloth over boards; spines stamped in gold Bookplates of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library. Joint commission to adjust private claims of American citizens against the Mexican government, and of Mexican citizens against the U.S. government. Met July 31, 1869-1876 Jan. 31, with the umpire finishing 1876 Nov. 20. Each country had one commissioner at a time, and they chose an umpire. Typescript (carbon copy) transcript of awards. Of 1017 claims of U.S. citizens, 186 awards; of 998 claims of Mexicans, 167 awards. William Henry Wadsworth was the American member; Mexican members included Francisco Gomez Palacio and Manuel Maria de Zamacona. Umpires were Francis Lieber, and from 1872 Sir Edward Thornton. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 17f v.10 f

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 18; Typescript (carbon copy) of a speech, read May 26, 1921, possibly in Geneva, Switzerland; appendix contains color maps and clippings in French and Swedish as well as English. Traces the history of the islands and recommends they be awarded to Finland. Formerly Ind. Ms. Bd. 18.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 19. 1917 Nov. 3, F.W. Hirst [possibly Francis Wrigley Hirst] to the British and American censors explaining the background of the transcript. Bookplate of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library Purchase, 1950, Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. Typewritten transcript of: Considerations on peace and war, under the following heads: I. Whether it be the interest of the Allies to consent to a peace in this conjuncture. II. Upon what conditions a lasting peace may be expected. III. The means for obtaining such conditions. London : Printed for B. Bragge ..., 1710. Handwritten note on title page reads: Copied at the request of James Brown Scott of Washington from a pamphlet in the possession of Mr. Leo [sic] Strachey the editor of the Spectator. Formerly Ind. Ms. Bd. 19.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Lacking p. 106-125; stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on title page. Typescript issued by the Publicity Department of the Shanghai branch of the Central Executive Committee of the Chung-kuo kuo min tang, complaining to the League of Nations in Geneva about the Japanese invasion, 1931, of Manchuria; contains transcripts of statements of Chinese officials and other Chiniese people, of notes between China and Japan, and of notes between China and the United States. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 20f

did.unittitle: Brockdorff-Rantzau, Ulrich, Graf, Transcripts of Statements

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on first leaf. German diplomat, chairman of the German delegation at the Paris Peace Conference, until 1919 June 20, when he resigned. Typescript translation into English of replies to proposed reparations clauses in the Treaty of Versailles (between Germany and the Allied and Associated Powers), 1919 May 7, 21; reply of May 24 in English, French, and German. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 24f

did.unittitle: Memorandum on the Treaty of St. Germain

odd.p: Ms. memorandum, sent by the Osterreichische Volkerbundliga to the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, concerning the need for revisions in clauses, particularly financial clauses, in the Treaty of St. Germain between the Allied and Associated Powers and Austria. Includes transcripts of sections, some in English, some in German, some in French, by Emanuel Vogel, Julius Deutsch, and others. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 25f

did.unittitle: American Commission to Negotiate Peace Papers

odd.p: "S-H Bulletin no. 252." Stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on first leaf; stamped Secret. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 26f

did.unittitle: Notes to the Paris Peace Conference

odd.p: Marshall of France, and commmander of the Allied forces at the end of World War I. Typescripts in French. Foch writes to the Paris Peace Conference: Oct. 14, enclosing a note from the German government explaining why some clauses in the Treaty of Versailles have not been carried out; Oct. 23, enclosing a list of clauses of the treaty that have not yet been executed; Nov. 19, enclosing an estimation of expenses of the Allied and Associated Powers in various occupied territories. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 27f

odd.p: Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 29f. Assistant technical adviser in international law to the American Commission to Negotiate Peace, 1918-19. Associated with the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace, 1914-30. Typescript (carbon copy), analyzes treaty provisions, 1797-1916, chiefly of European and American treaties, concerning transfer of sovereignty. Has chronological list of treaties discussed. Probably prepared in 1919 during the Paris Peace Conference. Formerly Ind. Ms. Bd. 29.

odd.head: General note
odd.p: The American Commission was the American delegation to the Paris Peace Conference, 1919-1920. Typescripts of the American delegation's copies of certain reports, 62-108, of decisions, translated probably from French into English, arrived at during the Paris Peace Conference. Includes: conditions for raising blockade of Germany; transcripts of correspondence with A.V. Kolchak about political situation in the Soviet Union; transcripts of correspondence with Dutch government about possible return of German Kaiser to Germany. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 30f

odd.p: Typescript transcripts of resolutions no. 0-108, prepared for the American Commission. Resolutions are chiefly short, and concern procedural matters, and policy matters of treaties with Austria, Bulgaria, and Hungary. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 31 v.1

odd.head: General note

Director of Bibliotheque du palais de la paix, The Hague, Netherlands. Claims that William Ladd was the author of A dissertation on a congress of nations, in reply to the assertion of Edson L. Whitney that the author was Thomas C. Upham. Includes 2-leaf TLS, 1928 Aug. 2, from Whitney to Mary Alice Matthews explaining that he believes neither Upham or Ladd was the author of the work. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 33f

did.unittitle: Women and Peace : Address on Women in International Affairs at the Century of Progress: Typescript

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on first leaf. Settlement worker, founder of Hull House, peace activist. Describes peace work of women's groups in the 19th and 20th centuries, including the work of the Women's International League for Peace and Freedom, of which she was president. Speech was presented at the Century of Progress International Exposition, Chicago, 1933. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 35f

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Bound in brown paper covers. Ms. note on cover giving published title. Ms. note on title page mentions letter from Shotwell about published version. Stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on cover. Confidential proof for members of the Committee on Problems and Policy of the Social Science Research Council and of the American National Committee on Internatinal Cooperation. Collaborators include: George A. Finch, Edith E. Ware, A. Curtis Wilgus, Edward R. Murrow, Heber Harper, Alice Cheyney, Carol Riegelman. Edited by Grover Clark. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 37

odd.head: General note
odd.p: Report concerns postwar conditions in England, Belgium, and Holland; the work of the Inter-parliamentary Union; and the formation of the League of Nations. Norwegian Nobel Peace Prize laureate, 1921; secretary-general, Inter-parliamentary Union, 1909-1933; member, Norwegian delegation to League of Nations, 1920-1938. Report concerns postwar conditions in England, Belgium, and Holland; the work of the Inter-parliamentary Union; and the formation of the League of Nations. Provenance: At head of title: For the trustees of the Carnegie Endowment only. Strictly confidential. "Copy for Dr. James Brown Scott, May 19, 1919." Stamp of Carnegie Endowment for International Peace Library on title page. Formerly call number: Ind. Ms. Bd. 38

Summary: Copies of documents that Lutz collected to write a legal article about a case, which concerned the British government's attempt to recover restitution for the death of James Pugh, an Irish seaman, at the hands of Panamanian police officers.
